That&#39;s what will happen if the Fed hikes interest rates
A rate hike is coming and the bull market will falter, bond yields will rise and the economy will slide into recession.
We know this.
What we don&#39;t know is how long this will all last and how long it will last.
In particular, for business, history offers little guidance on how to proceed.
A recession came within just 11 months of the first rate hike and lasted 86 months.
The aggressiveness of the Federal Reserve in raising interest rates is often, if not always, a factor in how the economy and financial assets react.
That&#39;s why Federal Reserve officials have been so vehement that investors shouldn&#39;t focus on when it will start raising interest rates, but rather on the time it takes for the rate to normalize.
In fact, several variables play a role.
In the end, however, market participants may find that all the excitement about a rate hike may have been overdone.
&quot;The Fed&#39;s first hike since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as signaling the end of the &#39;easy money&#39; era,&quot; said Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, in a note to clients.
In contrast, we do not expect US interest rates to gradually return to normal levels, but still at levels too low to trigger the seismic shock that many seem to fear.
However, that doesn&#39;t mean there won&#39;t be an impact.
Here&#39;s a look at how some areas of the economy might react, based on historical trends:
As the market has seen over the past month, anticipating rate hikes can make things volatile for a while.
Once the raise arrives, the impact isn&#39;t as dramatic.
&quot;There appears to be a tendency for asset returns to stall 12 to 24 months after the first hike, perhaps again reflecting the lag in monetary policy,&quot; Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study of what happens after the Fed hikes rates .
More specifically, the market has been mostly up for the past 35 years - about 14 percent - on the way to a rate hike, fairly flat in the 250 days thereafter (average gain of 2.6 percent), then back to normal after 500 days, with an average return over the past six cycles of 14.4 percent, according to a recent analysis published by Barron&#39;s Bob Doll, chief investment strategist at Nuveen Asset Management.
Deutsche Bank said the impact on stocks tends to come later in the appreciation cycle and the yield begins to decline.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but they are often fueled by interest rate hikes.
In the current case, the Fed faces some conditions that did not exist before that could accelerate a recession.
Most notably, gross domestic product will be near its lowest point if the Fed hikes rates.
According to Deutsche Bank, of the 118 rate hikes since 1950, nominal GDP has only fallen below 4.5 percent twice.
Although the second quarter of 2015 came in at 3.6 percent, few expect this to continue, expecting just 1.5 percent for the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Raising rates in such a fragile economic backdrop could be risky, raising the question &quot;whether it&#39;s different this time,&quot; Deutsche Bank said.
Market participants have been bracing for a Fed rate hike all year and all eyes have been on this week&#39;s Federal Open Market Committee meeting, which ends on Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe the FOMC could approve a hike this session, futures trading is only listing a 25 percent probability.
&quot;In our study, all cycles of increases from 1950 to the present have occurred in a super-cycle with accelerating momentum in GDP, dwarfing pre-recession highs very quickly after the recovery began,&quot; says the report.
In contrast, this is a decidedly slow recovery from what was the worst recession of the period under review.
The current cycle is by far the longest the Fed has waited since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, and this is 74 months so far.
Fixed income has also been volatile as the market anticipates a rate hike and the pattern is quite similar to the capital market.
The main difference is that bonds act faster than stocks when they change their strategic course.
For bonds, yields seem to reverse direction once the first hike/cut in the cycle occurs.
