&#39;Sonogenetics&#39; can control brain cells through sound waves
The video shows how the nematodes change direction the moment they are irradiated with sound pulses.
Scientists have bred worms with genetically modified nervous systems that can be controlled by bursts of sound waves.
The tiny nematodes change direction the moment they are irradiated with sound pulses that have frequencies too high for human hearing to hear.
The impulses work by turning on motor neuron cells, which are genetically modified to carry membrane channels that respond to ultrasonic waves.
More on this topic: Researchers read and write brain activity with light
The researchers said the worms demonstrated the power of a new technique, called sonogenetics, in which ultrasound can be used to activate a range of brain, heart and muscle cells outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told the Guardian the procedure could one day replace deep brain stimulation, an invasive procedure that delivers electrical pulses into people&#39;s brains to treat the symptoms of Parkinson&#39;s disease .
Roundworms don&#39;t typically respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that they did when surrounded by a liquid containing microscopic air bubbles.
The bubbles, he found, amplify the ultrasonic waves, which then penetrate the worms.
The amplified ultrasonic waves act on structures called TRP-4 ion channels found in the membranes of some of the worm&#39;s cells.
The sound waves cause these ion channels to open and activate the cells they are associated with, according to a report Nature Communications.
To create ultrasound-gated nematodes, Chalasani genetically engineered the worms so that some of their motoneurons carry TRP-4 ion channels.
When he applies ultrasound to the altered creatures, the sound waves are amplified by the microbubbles and transmitted into the worms, where they turn on the altered motor neurons.
The technique shares some similarities with Optogenetics, a pioneering tool that allows scientists to turn neurons on and off with pulses of light.
But Chalasani said Sonogenetics may have some advantages over this technique.
Unlike light, which must be sent down an optical fiber to the desired location in the brain, low-frequency ultrasound waves can pass through tissue unhindered and so can be launched into the brain from the top of the skull.
&quot;We believe that with gene therapy and a therapeutic virus, it is possible to make the targeted human neurons transiently vulnerable to the ultrasound signal in a clinical setting for certain neurological treatments,&quot; Chalasani said.
Other applications could focus on muscle cells and insulin-producing cells, he added.
