At their most anticipated meeting of the year, Federal Reserve strategists are spending two days this week seated around a 27-foot Honduran mahogany table to decide whether it&#39;s time to raise interest rates for the first time in nearly a decade.
A mural of the United States looms over them at one end of the ornate, two-story boardroom.
The card is a reminder that Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the nation&#39;s economic interests above all else.
The Fed has a dual mandate from Congress: maximize US employment and keep prices here stable.
But since the Great Recession, Fed leaders have recognized that there is an unwritten third mandate: financial stability.
And that third mandate could be the X factor in a decision too narrow to predict. It will be announced on Thursday whether the US economy is ready to start being weaned from the unprecedented stimulus provided by the near-zero short-term interest rate since late 2008.
Although most data on the economy shows that it is growing solidly, the recent turmoil in global financial markets could make the already cautious Fed officials fearful of amplifying that volatility by raising Bund yields -- if only by a quarter percentage point.
&quot;Obviously, the primary thing they&#39;re going to watch is the labor market and inflation,&quot; said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus &amp; Co.
&quot;But I think if they were looking for an excuse not to hike interest rates, the heightened uncertainty surrounding the global market is enough justification to continue to wait,&quot; she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself is unsettling the financial market.
About half of the economists recently polled by Bloomberg have predicted a rate hike this week.
However, financial markets are expecting a wait-and-see for the Fed, with a key indicator showing only a 30% chance of a hike.
This suggests the stock market will fall if the Fed hikes rates unless strategists soften the blow by promising that another hike is far away.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average jumped 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The action was prompted by expectations that Fed policy would keep rates up this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody&#39;s Capital Markets Research Group.
It would be a surprise if the Fed hiked rates at this point,&quot; he said.
If she does, &quot;she would have to go very far in her statement to reassure financial markets that they don&#39;t panic.&quot;
Other pundits argued that a rate hike would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about when the Fed will act.
Just a month ago, the Fed appeared on track to hike rates by 0.25 percentage point this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would test the strength of the US recovery.
Yellen had said in the spring and early summer that she expected the rate to rise this year, despite complaints from Liberals that more economic progress was needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, the improvement in the labor market this year has been solid.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years and near what the Fed considers full employment.
Wage increases have shown signs of recovery.
And although inflation has remained consistently below the central bank&#39;s 2% target for the year, Fed officials said the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy &quot;can handle higher interest rates and needs it because of the tightening job market,&quot; said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world twitched late last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial average fell more than 16% from its peak in May as investors feared a slowdown in China&#39;s economy would choke global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, with the Dow now down almost 10% from the May high.
For Fed officials, the market turmoil is affecting the complex calculation of when to raise rates.
&quot;If the events in financial markets and the news of weakness in the Chinese economy hadn&#39;t occurred over the past few weeks, they would be tightening the reins at this session,&quot; said Stephen D. Oliner, senior research fellow at UCLA&#39;s Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Federal Reserve employee.
Now he predicts she will wait at least a month to get a better handle on the effects.
&quot;There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact on the US economy will be and there is almost no reliable data describing developments in China,&quot; Oliner said.
The health of the global economy is not one of the Fed&#39;s primary concerns, so technically it shouldn&#39;t be involved in its decision-making.
But the bottom line is that the Fed has become the monetary authority of the world.
The influence of the central bank has been enormous in recent years.
Then-Chairman Ben S. Bernanke&#39;s mere suggestion in 2013 that the Fed could &quot;tighten&quot; its monetary expansion sparked confusion around the globe.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly interdependent, Fed officials can be expected not only to monitor developments elsewhere, but also to consult with other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the sustain global economy.
Their decision-making is &quot;more art than science,&quot; said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy for wealth management at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, President of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., noted this month that &quot;the Fed has a history of overreacting to financial market moves that appear unrelated to economic fundamentals.&quot;
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee that campaigns for a rate hike, cited decisions in 1998-1999 as an example.
A financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to cut interest rates by 0.75 percentage points in three meetings &quot;despite a limited discernible impact on US growth,&quot; Lacker said.
A year later, the Fed officials reversed those cuts.
The Fed should only prioritize financial stability issues during a major crisis like the 2008 market meltdown, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England&#39;s Rate Setting Committee.
The recent turmoil doesn&#39;t come close to that level, he said.
&quot;She certainly doesn&#39;t want to get into the situation where she&#39;s afraid of a rate hike because the markets are upset,&quot; said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still has the dual mandate and makes no mention of financial stability and until that is changed I don&#39;t think it should be ahead of the curve.
