For slightly overweight diabetics, weight loss surgery can be helpful.
The benefits of weight-loss surgery for slightly obese people with type 2 diabetes may last at least five years, according to a new study.
It&#39;s too early to tell if slightly obese people with diabetes live longer after weight loss surgery than those who receive nonsurgical treatments.
&quot;The mortality data takes a long time to show anything,&quot; said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in weight loss surgery, who wrote an editorial on the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight loss surgeries, or bariatric surgery, use different methods to decrease the size of the stomach.
They reduce hunger and limit the body&#39;s ability to absorb food.
Over the years, obesity surgery has proven effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted in people who are morbidly obese with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or greater.
BMI, a measure of weight-to-height, is considered normal between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or more indicates someone is overweight, and people with a BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, the researchers from Taiwan&#39;s Min-Sheng General Hospital used data collected since 2007 in a study comparing two types of bariatric surgery -- gastric bypass and gastric tube construction -- to medical treatments for type 2 diabetes in humans who were slightly overweight.
The average BMI among those who underwent the surgery fell from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year in this study.
Meanwhile, among those receiving non-surgical diabetes treatments, BMI remained about the same at 29.
Among those who underwent surgery, 36% had complete diabetes resolution and 28% had partial resolution.
In comparison, in the medically treated group, diabetes completely resolved in only 1 percent and partially in only about 2 percent.
In addition, outcomes in controls for blood pressure, triglycerides, and &quot;bad&quot; LDL cholesterol &quot;were generally better in the &#39;surgical&#39; group,&quot; the authors found.
The researchers also monitored the patient&#39;s blood levels of hemoglobin A1c, which reflect blood glucose levels over time.
Hemoglobin A1c is best kept below 7 percent, the researchers write.
After the operation, the average hemoglobin A1c level dropped from around 9 percent to around 6 percent.
In the medical therapy group, however, it remained stable at about 8 percent.
But this better &quot;glycemic control&quot; -- as reflected in improved hemoglobin A1c levels -- did not reduce mortality at five years, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and his colleagues.
The research team also compared average results from the two types of surgery.
By year five, the bypass surgery group had lost more weight (18.7 vs. 14.2 kg), achieved greater reductions in BMI (7.4 vs. 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3, 1% vs. 2.1%) and were more likely to achieve complete resolution of diabetes (46.9% vs. 16.7%).
While the new study doesn&#39;t show a five-year survival benefit from surgery, there is evidence from a study of heavier people in Sweden that surgery leads to longer lives, says Blackstone of the University of Arizona, College of Medicine Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery were about 29 percent less likely to die over 15 years compared to a group who tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study didn&#39;t show a survival benefit for the surgery patients, Blackstone said it&#39;s reassuring for people with a BMI below 35 who are interested in the procedure.
&quot;That&#39;s the critical point of this study because it says this surgery is lower in this lower BMI group&quot; with no increased risk of death or kidney disease, she said.
Blackstone added that once the patient&#39;s BMI is between 27 and 30, people and their doctors should start taking weight seriously.
&quot;I think we&#39;re waiting too long to get people to take this seriously,&quot; she said.
I think once they&#39;ve accumulated these genetic changes that have hardwired their bodies to obesity and diabetes, it&#39;s really hard to reverse.&quot;
