&quot;A kid doesn&#39;t think this is bad for them,&quot; Lopez said.
Many of the more appealing (hand sanitizers) are the ones that are scented.
There are strawberry, grape and orange scented disinfectants that are very appealing to children.
Hand sanitizers contain anywhere from 45 to 95 percent alcohol.
Even a few splashes can lead to alcohol poisoning, especially in small children.
&quot;It&#39;s highly concentrated alcohol,&quot; said Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the poison control center at the University of Kansas Hospital, Fox 4 in Kansa City.
Now, you wouldn&#39;t leave a sip of whiskey lying around, but people keep these hand sanitizers within reach of children, and when children get at it, it&#39;s a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who recently ingested four squirts of strawberry-scented hand sanitizer at school, was taken to an emergency room for treatment.
Her blood alcohol concentration was 179, twice the threshold for an adult to be legally intoxicated, said Dr. Chris Ritchey, an emergency room physician who treated her at Gwinnett Medical Center outside of Atlanta.
Nhaijah slurred her words and was unable to walk when she arrived at the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight at a separate children&#39;s hospital for signs of brain trauma because the girl had fallen from drinking and hit her head, Ritchey said.
&quot;That was very scary,&quot; Ortoria Scott, Nhaijah&#39;s mother, told CNN.
It could have been fatal to my child.
Lopez has advised parents and teachers to use alcohol-free products or disinfectant wipes, and to store hand sanitizer out of child&#39;s reach.
Beyond alcohol poisoning, some disinfectants have been associated with fatalities.
In 2013, two Ontario women died after swallowing hand sanitizer that contained a toxic undeclared ingredient.
Health officials suspect the product contained methanol, a deadly solution, rather than ethyl alcohol, which has been listed as the active ingredient.
In January, three fourth-grade students in New York state plotted to poison their &quot;mean&quot; teacher by placing antibacterial products around the classroom,&quot; according to a police report.
