According to migration researcher Dietrich Thränhardt, work is the key to social contacts, to being valued in the receiving society, but also to the self-esteem of immigrants.
According to Thränhardt, there has been a political change in Germany: from a ban on refugees working to recognition of work.
While there used to be a ban on work for asylum seekers of up to five years, this was reduced to three months in November 2014, as was the residence requirement, which limits asylum seekers to one place of residence.
In society - also because of the shortage of skilled workers - the majority view has prevailed that refugees should be given faster access to the labor market.
A major hurdle for access to the job market is a lack of German language skills.
So far there has not been a sufficient range of general and job-related language courses.
Studies also show that jobs are most often mediated through personal contacts.
