As a result of European decisions, Germany has had an anti-discrimination agency and a general equality law for almost a decade.
But it learns very slowly, as the NSU series of murders showed, in which the police and authorities systematically ignored the racist motive.
Equal opportunities for everyone: What migrant organizations and the interest groups of non-white Germans have been demanding for a long time and what international agreements such as the Anti-Racism Convention oblige Germany to do must become reality in the next few years if the country is to remain peaceful and its new citizens are to make use of their opportunities - for example good of all.
