This wobbling movement is small, but still too large for a continuously fixed celestial body, according to a statement from Cornell University in Ithaca (US state New York) on Tuesday.
The researchers present their analyzes in the journal &quot;Icarus&quot;.
It has long been known that there must be liquid water beneath the Enceladus ice sheet.
In 2006, for example, &quot;Cassini&quot; discovered ice volcanoes at the south pole of Saturn&#39;s moon that spew water vapor and ice particles and thus feed Saturn&#39;s so-called E ring.
At least at the South Pole there must be an underground sea, the astronomers concluded at the time.
However, the extent of the hidden ocean was not clear.
