Hammer Artist invested three years in the personal interpretation of the Bible
Jesus with the (gilded) crown of thorns is one of the main works that Otmar Alt painted for his Bible.
Klaus Altepost wrote the introduction and updated Bible texts.
In the beginning was the Word?
No, not with the Otmar Alt Bible, which has now been published with magnificent pictures.
In the beginning was the picture for Otmar Alt, who formulated his very personal interpretations of biblical stories on paper and canvas in 150 motifs.
The 75-year-old has retained his &quot;language&quot; with bright colors and imaginative shapes - but this is by no means synonymous with &quot;funny&quot; pictures.
On the contrary: Adapted to the respective topics, it can seem quite gloomy.
Otmar Alt worked on his Bible project for around three years, for which he made a subjective-artistic selection from the many subject areas of the &quot;Book of All Books&quot;.
Cycles were created that deal with topics such as the Way of the Cross, plagues, commandments or the Lord&#39;s Prayer.
In doing so, he spontaneously fascinated several partners: This applies to the Luther publishing house with its theological orientation as well as to the Kettler publishing house with its focus on art books.
And there is above all the author Klaus Altepost, who has dealt with the respective Bible passages on the basis of the painting.
He interpreted the Bible passages selected by Otmar Alt and thus &quot;translated&quot; them into today&#39;s current context.
These texts are like verbal mirrors of Alt&#39;s paintings.
They are embedded between the original quotation from the Bible by Martin Luther and a sentence by the artist, who is formulating his very personal thoughts on the respective situation.
The decorative binding has golden letters.
In this way, the 75-year-old allows a deep insight into his soul and his emotions in two ways.
That&#39;s a high level of intimacy.
Ultimately, emotions were what triggered the Bible project in the first place: Otmar Alt, born in Wernigerode in 1940 and raised in Berlin, comes from a family that belonged to the strict Protestant Moravian Order.
&quot;The education used to be done with a cane,&quot; remembers Otmar Alt.
&quot;I tried to work through that, so that I might get along with my father again.&quot;
His second concern is to help art regain its status in fast-moving times: &quot;Today, the perception of visual worlds is shaped by advertising, and it&#39;s loud.
Symbolism is suppressed there.
Artists have a different lust and delight in showing things.
Pictures always have something mysterious and are not decorative.
&quot;In that sense, I&#39;m a dinosaur&quot;.
Otmar Alt wants the viewer to &quot;fall into&quot; the pictures, let them affect them, discover and feel the power they have: &quot;The picture looks for its counterpart&quot;.
Klaus Altepost admitted on Tuesday at the presentation of the Otmar Alt Bible in the Otmar Alt Foundation that he had &quot;always&quot; been a lover of Otmar Alt&#39;s art: &quot;I like how he understands life with his pictures&quot;.
Alt didn&#39;t make sure to fully understand the Bible, but chose the topics that were important to him and also mysterious.
&quot;It wasn&#39;t an equal partnership,&quot; says Altepost: &quot;This is about the pictures, the text just explains.&quot; A picture Bible was created.
For Hans Möhler from Luther Verlag, this work is an invitation to &quot;deepen your life and find freedom&quot;.
For Möhler, Otmar Alt&#39;s pictures speak both the (biblical) language of love and that of responsibility.
